SIMPLE: felicitate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Felicitate
<hw>Fe*lic"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>felicitatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>felicitare</ets> to felicitate,
fr. <ets>felix</ets>, <ets>-icis</ets>, happy. See
<er>felicity</er>.]</ety> <def>Made very happy.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am alone <qex>felicitate</qex>⟦br⟧
In your dear highness' love.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Felicitate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Felicitate
<hw>Fe*lic"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Felicitated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>felicitating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>f⟦eacute⟧liciter</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make very happy;
to delight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What a glorious entertainment and pleasure would fill and
<qex>felicitate</qex> his spirit.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To express joy or pleasure to; to wish felicity to;
to call or consider (one's self) happy; to congratulate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every true heart must <qex>felicitate</qex> itself that its lot is
cast in this kingdom.</q> <rj><qau>W. Howitt.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Congratulate</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Felicitation</ent>⟦br⟧
